The European "Green Deal"
NEW YORK – Europe has done it.
The "Green Deal for Europe" announced by the European Commission is, to date, the first comprehensive sustainable development plan decided upon by a major region of the planet.
It thus becomes a landmark for the entire world—a guide for transforming toward a prosperous, socially inclusive, and ecologically sustainable economy, the first agenda for everyone to achieve this goal.
Of course, the task awaiting Europeans is impressive.
Even the reading of the documents recently made public reveals a first impression of a lavish array of plans, consultations, regulatory frameworks, laws, budgets, and diplomacy, involving a large number of interconnected and related subjects ranging from energy to transportation, from food to industry.
His detractors will mock European bureaucracy.
But it is a bureaucracy in the best Weberian sense of the term: it is rational.
The Sustainable Development Goals are clearly stated, the targets are defined based on goals set with deadlines, and programs and procedures are adapted to the targets.
Overall, the stated ambition is to achieve "carbon neutrality" (net zero emissions of greenhouse gases) by 2050, to establish a circular economy that ends the destructive pollution caused by plastics and other petrochemical derivatives, pesticides, and toxic waste, and to implement a "farm to table" food system that does not harm people by feeding them overly processed industrial products, nor harms the Earth through unsustainable agricultural practices.
And the European Commission understands that the method to achieve this must be based on the citizens themselves.
Once again, critics will view the announcements of public consultations as mere window-dressing.
But go ahead and speak of pointless chatter to French President Emmanuel Macron, who has faced riots for over a year, or to Chilean President Sebastián Piñera, whose country suddenly erupted this autumn following a minor increase in metro ticket prices.
Macron and Piñera are both convinced of the necessity of ecological change.
Both have committed to achieving carbon neutrality in their countries by 2050.
And both are desperately trying to figure out how to organize or structure a public consultation, but after the fact.
American advocates of neoliberalism will once again mock and claim that the "market" will know how to address climate change.
But one only needs to look at today's United States.
If neoliberalism treats the planet the way it has treated American infrastructure, we all have reason to be concerned.
Arriving at an airport in the United States means enduring elevators, escalators, broken shuttles, taxis that don't arrive, nonexistent rail connections, highways whose lanes are in such bad condition that they can't be used, replaced by detours.
The reason for these malfunctions is simple: corruption.
Each American election cycle today costs 8 billion dollars, or even more, and its funding is provided by billionaires, major oil companies, the military-industrial complex, the healthcare industry lobby, and interest groups determined to lower taxes and protect the status quo at all costs.
The solutions offered by the market are a farce when politics is subject to all the influences emanating from it, as is the case in the United States.
The European Green Deal shows what a government should be like, not a government subordinate to the interests of businesses.
The European Green Deal in fact demonstrates the success of European social democracy (in its operational sense and not strictly partisan).
A mixed economy, combining markets, the regulatory power of the state, the public sector, and civil society, will pursue a mixed strategy: public objectives, public investments in infrastructure, private investments in industrial transformation, research and development missions based on public-private partnerships, and an informed population.
In fact, it is an industrial policy at its most sophisticated level.
(I recently outlined, in broad terms, what a social democratic Green New Deal strategy would look like for the United States.)
We have reasons to be optimistic.
The most important point is that advanced technologies, which will enable the creation of an advanced, decarbonized, resource-efficient, and therefore ecologically sustainable economy, already exist at the commercial or pre-commercial stage.
By combining renewable energy, digital technologies, advanced materials, and collaborative economy models in transportation or other infrastructure, we can decarbonize the energy system, transition to a circular economy, and drastically reduce the flow of primary resources.
But for this, three major challenges must be addressed.
The first is to overcome the interests that seek to maintain the status quo.
The major oil companies will have to absorb the losses, but workers in the sector and mining regions should receive compensation in the form of income support, retraining programs, and other public assistance.
The European plan rightly claims a "just transition."
The second challenge is that of financing.
Europe, as well as other regions of the world, will need to redirect a relatively small portion of its production, between 1% and 2%, towards the green economy, particularly concerning new infrastructure, public procurement, research and development, industrial equipment renewal, etc. Funding will come from the private sector, but also from public budgets.
Europe must stand up to the ideologues who oppose an increase in EU spending.
The facts must be taken into account.
The last major challenge is diplomatic.
Europe represents about 9.1% of global carbon dioxide emissions, while China's share is 30% and that of the United States is 14%.
Even if Europe manages to fully implement its Green Deal, it will be in vain if other regions of the world do not join it in this fight.
European leaders therefore rightly consider that diplomacy is fundamental to the success of the Green Deal.
Let's take the example of China.
After decades of rapid growth, which eliminated mass poverty, China has become the world's largest emitter of CO2 (although its emissions per capita remain half those of the United States).
China alone will determine the future of the global climate.
On the one hand, Chinese leaders know that their country is extremely vulnerable to climate change and risks diplomatic isolation if they do not make sufficient efforts to decarbonize; on the other hand, they must face the dangers of the unfortunate cold war launched by America.
Hardliners within the government and Chinese coal lobbies are resisting decarbonization efforts, especially since Trump himself rejects it, despite pressure from the United States.
European diplomacy can make a difference if it refuses to go along with America's subtle measures to hinder China and instead offers the latter a positive, unambiguous partnership: working together to build sustainable infrastructure, development, and technology across Eurasia, within the framework of a Chinese Green Deal comparable to Europe's.
Such a partnership would be of immense benefit to Europe, China, and the dozen Eurasian countries that lie between them, not to mention the world as a whole.
Europe has taken a historic step with its ambitious, mobilizing, and feasible plan.
The Green Deal is a powerful signal of hope in a world of uncertainties and instability.
